 Glyn-Nedd, Glmrgn, Wls":"Glamorgan, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","of Glyn-Nedd, Glmrgn., Wls.":"Glamorgan, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"abt. 1420–":"about 1420–Deceased","1418–Male":"1418–Deceased","1420–Male":"1420–Deceased","1422–Male":"1422–Deceased","1424–Male":"1424–Deceased","1426–Female":"1426–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1450–Male":"1450–Deceased","1452–Female":"1452–Deceased","1454–Female":"1454–Deceased","1390–Male":"1390–Deceased","1395–Female":"1395–Deceased","abt. 1452":"about 1452","1395":"1395","1450":"1450","abt. 1454":"about 1454","abt. 1420":"about 1420","abt 1450":"about 1450","1390":"1390","1426":"1426","1424":"1424","1422":"1422","1454":"1454","1420":"1420","1452":"1452","1418":"1418","of Glyn-Nedd, Glmrgn, Wls":"Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","of Glyn-Nedd, Glmrgn., Wls.":"Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"ap","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Hungarian Geza, Jeno, Arpad, Attila, Csaba.","Hungarian: variant of   Papp  , meaning ‘priest (of the Catholic or Orthodox Church)’. This surname is also found in Romania, Slovakia, Croatia, and Serbia, and also among Rusyns (in Serbia and Croatia). See also   Pop   2 and   Popa  .","English: variant of   Pape   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Papp","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Hungarian Laszlo, Zoltan, Geza, Istvan, Gabor, Miklos, Tibor, Arpad, Denes, Imre, Attila.","German (Bavaria, Tyrol): from Middle High German <i>pap</i> ‘baby food’, Dutch <i>pap</i> ‘porridge, pap’, hence perhaps a nickname denoting someone who had lost his teeth or subsisted on a meager diet.","Hungarian: from <i>pap</i> ‘priest (of the Catholic or Orthodox Church)’, probably an occupational name for someone in the service of a priest or a nickname for a pious person. This surname is also found in Romania and Slovakia, and also among Rusyns. Compare   Pap   and   Pop  ."]}]},{"name":"David","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Jewish, Welsh, Scottish, English, French, Breton, Portuguese, Czech, Croatian, and Slovenian; Hungarian (<b>Dávid</b>), Slovak (mainly <b>Dávid</b>): from the Hebrew personal name <i>David</i> (in Hungarian and Slovak spelled <i>Dávid</i>), interpreted as ‘beloved’. The name has been perennially popular among Jews, in honor of the Biblical king of this name. His prominence, and the vivid narrative of his life contained in the First Book of Samuel, led to adoption of the name among Christians in the Middle Ages in various parts of Europe. In Britain, the popularity of this as a personal name was increased for two reasons. Firstly by virtue of its being the name of the patron saint of Wales who was abbot-bishop in the 6th century at what became known as Saint David's in Pembrokeshire. There are numerous dedications and placenames honouring the saint in south Wales, and it is no coincidence that the modern surname is heavily concentrated there, especially in Glamorgan. Secondly, the name was borne by two kings of Scotland (David I, reigning 1124–53, and David II, 1329–71). Its popularity in Russia is largely due to the fact that this was the ecclesiastical name adopted by Saint Gleb (died 1015), one of two sons of Prince Vladimir of Kiev who were martyred for their Christian zeal. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from some other languages, especially Assyrian/Chaldean   Dawid   and Arabic   Daud   (with variants, such as   Daoud   and   Dawood  ).","History: Guillaume David from France married Marie Armand in Trois-Rivières, QC, in 1656. — This surname is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of America."],"variants":[{"name":"Davi","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Salvatore, Antonio, Guido, Rosario, Mario, Sal, Calogero, Gino, Vincenzo, Vito, Alessandra, Biagio, Biago, Carmela.","Italian (Sicily; also <b>Davì</b>): perhaps from an altered form of the personal name <i>Davide</i> (see   David  ).","Italian (northern, mainly Veneto): from the personal name <i>Davio</i>, a variant of   Davino  ."]},{"name":"Dauti","meanings":["Albanian: from the Albanian Muslim personal name <i>Daut</i> (definite form <i>Dauti</i>), from Turkish <i>Davud</i>, an equivalent of   David  ."]},{"name":"Davey","meanings":["English: from the personal name <i>Davy</i>, originally an Old French vernacular form of the Biblical name   David   which became the most common form of the name in medieval England."]},{"name":"Daviau","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Aime, Aldor, Emile, Normand.","French: from a derivative of <i>Davi</i>, a vernacular form of the personal name   David  . Compare   Davio   and   Devoid  ."]},{"name":"Davide","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Salvatore, Gandolfo, Marco.","Italian: from the personal name <i>Davide</i>, an equivalent of   David  ."]},{"name":"Dawid","meanings":["Polish: from the personal name <i>Dawid</i>, Polish form of the Biblical name   David  .","Assyrian/Chaldean: from the personal name <i>Dāwīd</i>, Syriac form of the Biblical name   David  . It is often spelled in the Arabized form   Daud   (or   Daoud   and   Dawood  )."]},{"name":"Ben-David","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Shula, Ilan, Meir, Meyer, Ari, Avi, Ayal, Haim, Limor, Menashe, Mordechai, Moshe.","Jewish (from North Africa and the Ottoman Empire; also <b>Bendavid</b>): patronymic from the personal name   David   + Hebrew or vernacular Arabic <i>ben</i> ‘son’."]},{"name":"Daud","meanings":["Arabic: from the personal name <i>Dāwūd</i>, Arabic form of the Biblical name   David  . In Islam, Dāwūd is regarded as a messenger of God/Allah. Among Christians this name is found in part as an Arabized form of the Assyrian/Chaldean variant   Dawid  . Compare   Daoud   and   Dawood  ."]},{"name":"Davidenko","meanings":["Ukrainian (standard transliteration <b>Davydenko</b>): patronymic from the personal name <i>Davyd</i> (see   David  ), formed with the diminutive suffix <i>-enko</i>."]},{"name":"Dacus","meanings":["Welsh: Anglicized form of the personal name <i>Deicws</i>, a pet form of <i>Dafydd</i>, Welsh form of   David  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"Gitto","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["of Yiddish origin, originally a nickname meaning ‘good’ (modern German <i>gut</i>)."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Gitto ap David was born about 1420, in Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom, his father, David ap Jenkin, was 32 and his mother, Gwirvil ap Morgan, was 27. He had at least 1 son with Wenllian ap William."},"et":{"abt. 1420–":"umbes 1420–Surnud","1418–Male":"1418–Surnud","1420–Male":"1420–Surnud","1422–Male":"1422–Surnud","1424–Male":"1424–Surnud","1426–Female":"1426–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1450–Male":"1450–Surnud","1452–Female":"1452–Surnud","1454–Female":"1454–Surnud","1390–Male":"1390–Surnud","1395–Female":"1395–Surnud","abt. 1452":"umbes 1452","1395":"1395","1450":"1450","abt. 1454":"umbes 1454","abt. 1420":"umbes 1420","abt 1450":"umbes 1450","1390":"1390","1426":"1426","1424":"1424","1422":"1422","1454":"1454","1420":"1420","1452":"1452","1418":"1418","of Glyn-Nedd, Glmrgn, Wls":"Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","of Glyn-Nedd, Glmrgn., Wls.":"Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"abt. 1420–":"noin 1420–Kuollut","1418–Male":"1418–Kuollut","1420–Male":"1420–Kuollut","1422–Male":"1422–Kuollut","1424–Male":"1424–Kuollut","1426–Female":"1426–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1450–Male":"1450–Kuollut","1452–Female":"1452–Kuollut","1454–Female":"1454–Kuollut","1390–Male":"1390–Kuollut","1395–Female":"1395–Kuollut","abt. 1452":"noin 1452","1395":"1395","1450":"1450",